gw.pl.persistence.core.effdate.entity

Interface EffDatedBranch

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Bean, com.guidewire.commons.entity.BundleProvider, java.lang.Comparable<Bean>, Editable, EffDatedBase, Extractable, com.guidewire.pl.domain.extract.gen.ExtractableStubI, IGosuObject, com.guidewire.commons.entity.Keyable, KeyableBean, Retireable, com.guidewire.commons.entity.Sourceable, Versionable

    public interface EffDatedBranch
extends EffDatedBase, Retireable
    An EffDatedBranch, or simply branch, is the root of an effective dated [EffDated] graph. An EffDatedBranch itself is not effective dated, meaning that fields defined directly on the EffDatedBranch are consistent over the entire period range regardless of what slice date you're using to view the branch.

    Even though an EffDatedBranch doesn't have effective dated fields all the beans it refers to via links or arrays are effective dated. Therefore the branch will always be "sliced" or viewed as of a particular date, the slice date. By default the slice date is the EditEffectiveDate of the branch, which is typically set when the branch is created. You can use a different slice date by setting it yourself.

    Every branch belongs to a period, identified by its PeriodId. When a new submission or renewal is created the new branch is assigned a new PeriodId. When a new branch is created in the same period as another branch (e.g. a policy change) it shares the "based on" or "original" branch's PeriodId. A period often has several branches associated with it, both promoted and in draft, but will have only one "most recent" or "in-force" branch associated with it. This in-force branch is the most recently promoted branch associated with a period. The other promoted branches represent earlier versions of the in-force branch in model-time. Often when we refer to the "period" we're actually referring to the most recently bound branch in a period, ignoring the other, "older" branches that are also associated with the period.

    Periods themselves are grouped by their EffDatedContainer [think Policy]. Any two distinct periods within the same container cannot have overlapping period ranges. Or, you can't have two in-force branches in different periods with overlapping periods ranges within the same container.

    Whenever a bundle that includes a change to a branch or to a bean within the branch's graph is committed we obtain a database lock on the branch's container before doing any writes. This allows us to enforce several rules, such as that only one branch in a period can be the most recent and that no two periods overlap.

      • getPeriodId

        Key getPeriodId()
        Every branch belongs to a period, identified by its PeriodId. When a new submission or renewal is created the new branch is assigned a new PeriodId. When a new branch is created in the same period as another branch (e.g. a policy change) it shares the "based on" or "original" branch's PeriodId. A period often has several branches associated with it, both promoted and in draft, but will have only one "most recent" or "in-force" branch associated with it. This in-force branch is the most recently promoted branch associated with a period. The other promoted branches represent earlier versions of the in-force branch in model-time. Often when we refer to the "period" we're actually referring to the most recently bound branch in a period, ignoring the other, "older" branches that are also associated with the period.

        To find all the branches associated with a period find all branches with the same PeriodId.

        Returns:
        Period Id of this branch.

      • getAllEffectiveDates

        java.util.List<java.util.Date> getAllEffectiveDates()
        Returns a sorted list of distinct effective and expiration dates that exist on EffDated beans in the branch.

        Looking at every effective and expiration date of every bean in the branch to build this list is expensive. Call this once then cache the result if you know that the beans won't change while you use this information.

        Returns:
        A sorted list of distinct effective and expiration dates that exists in the branch.

      • setEditEffectiveDate

        void setEditEffectiveDate(java.util.Date effDate)
        Set the date at which edits to this branch are effective. By default a branch will always be "sliced" at this date. Changes made at this date to this branch or to any beans in this branch's graph are considered "slice" changes, changes made at any other effective date are "non-slice" changes.

        In the case changes were already made to the branch at effective dates after this effective date, only changes made at this edit effective will be considered OOS changes and can be potentially propagated forward to the future effective dates.

        It's assumed that the edit effective date doesn't change once it's set (it's typically set when the branch is created). If it is changed then changes made at the old edit effective date will become non-slice changes.

        Parameters:
        effDate - Date at which edits to this branch are effective.

      • getEditEffectiveDate

        java.util.Date getEditEffectiveDate()
        Date at which edits to this branch are effective. By default a branch will always be "sliced" at this date. Changes made at this date to this branch or to any beans in this branch's graph are considered "slice" changes, changes made at any other effective date are "non-slice" changes.
        Returns:
        Date at which edits to this branch are effective

      • getModelNumber

        java.lang.Integer getModelNumber()
        Model numbers are minted in the order in which a branch within this period is promoted, e.g. when a new submission is promoted its model number becomes 1, when a policy change on that submission is promoted its model number is 2, and so on. The branch with the highest model number is the "most recent" or "in-force" branch. Only a promoted branch will have a non-null model number.
        Returns:
        Model number of this branch if promoted, NULL otherwise.

      • isResolveWithFuturePeriods

        boolean isResolveWithFuturePeriods()
        When a branch is promoted and there exists a future bound period (or periods, but multiple would be rare) then this method returns true until it is cleared.

        This value can then be checked later to see if you want to apply the changes on this branch to that future period. Once it's cleared you will no longer have that option.

        Returns:
        True if when promoted there exited a future bound period.
